@popaganda. I've thought about this a lot lately - the idea that things outside myself happening randomly might result in something beautiful, non-2nd-law, that there's a future for my kids. Been struggling with the death of a very close friend for the last 6 months, and I (for some reason, I'm not going to defend or explain it) started reading the works of Rene Gerard, the mimetic desire philosopher ("Man is the creature who does not know what to desire, and he turns to others in order to make up his mind" etc.) Previously I had read more stoic philosophy and resonated with that. Historically I come from a Christian perspective, though never bought into evangelicalism even as a kid.

So, something very bad happened, and it rocked me harder than anything has in a long time. Spoke at my friend's memorial, told part of his life story, and wept with hundreds of people. Didn't end for me there, though. Became very... depressed is probably the wrong term. Nihilistic is closer, but also wrong. Maybe just "not hopeful".

Don't really have a logical conclusion for this, like I usually try to have, except to say: I still believe in beautiful things, people, experiences. Coffee while my kids chat with me in the morning. Sitting on the porch watching the sun rise earlier. And I do believe that all manner of things will be well in the end, and I choose to relax that tense knot inside myself, and I choose to move forward, and grow or decline, and move forward with as much grace as I can muster. I don't surf, and I find the overuse of the analogy annoying, but yes, to surf through the ups and downs instead of trying to master the waves.

@owenfraser I produced two songs on Four and was on tour with them and maybe even used this exact setup. They had these because every hotel room was different and the two engineers they had traveling with them were trying to consistently be able to isolate the vocal as best they could. The vocals that got recorded on tour were fine but far from ideal. 

You will be better served by treating your individual room, rather than trying to make a small booth-type thing. Vocals tend to sound uneven in the low mids when you record them in a small space. 

As @cian riordan said, lots of good info that is searchable on this discord about how to treat your room.

@oaklandmatt Thank you for the suggestions.

I'm very close to this point now. I'm doing 4 octave scale runs with both hands at various tempos to focus on consistency of fingering and of tone. The next frontier is doing a variation of these runs where one hand starts on a scale different interval (going up in 3rds, 4ths, etc...)

The exercise that's challenging me at the moment has been doing wide arpeggios (sometimes with intervals of a 7th or more) up and down a two octaves. I'm taking it slow and becoming more consistent, but I know I'm likely to start hitting a wall as I get them up to a quicker tempo, hence the renewed focus on really getting my technique right at these tempos.

I've very much internalized the concept of "Slow is smooth. Smooth is fast." I'm starting things slow and not moving on until I can do them flawlessly at glacial tempos.

@ehutton21 I think you're right about a teacher. LA is undoubtedly full of good ones. A lesson a week should help me to orient myself in the right direction.

Thank you for all of the insight.

@owengineered While singing “technique” may be something you might not want to get into until you are more used to singing, learning how to breathe well is never a bad thing. 

Eric Arceneaux is a legend, has great videos on fundamentals of breathing and relaxing exercises like yawns and knee bends. 

Scales and “vocal exercises” - probably not yet. But I think breathing exercises will do you good. There’s also a lot of misconceptions on breathing, like “breathe with belly” as opposed to diaphragm. But Eric Arceneaux’s videos on breathing cover this pretty well.
